Great coffee shop! Friendly workers and nice environment.

Excellent organic locally roasted coffee. One of the best cappuccinos around, never burned like some of the other places.

Their baked goods are unique and delicious as well,   If you have a chance to try the blackberry bar do it! You won‚Äôt regret it.< /review>

<Time>1619025017267< /Time><rating>5</rating><Review>We loved this little coffee shop and it was worth the drive from Fortuna in the morning to get ready for a day of touring around. Nice loose leaf green tea and great tasting coffee. Very friendly baristas and we really enjoyed the environment. Photos and art on the walls, a hand made kayak shop in the back, 1920's jazz playing, and lots of touches that give this place a lot of character and makes it one of the more memorable coffee shops we've visited. The town is beautiful to walk around on a soft morning.< /Review>< pics>

Unique, fun setting with a piano and violin available for any musician to play. < text>
This was such a cute place. My husband and I really liked mind's eye. We each ordered a cafe mocha with extra whipped cream and we shared a cream scone with blackberry jam. We sat by the fireplace and read the newspaper.   Check out the restroom if you get a chance to. It was one of those that has the water tank with the pull chain up high. It's actually quite an interesting restroom. A lot going on and worth checking out it feels kind of haunted. Mine's eye is walking distance to everything downtown old Town. We will definitely visit the next time we are in Ferndale.</text>

< text>
Really excellent coffee at a reasonable price.  This place is comfortable,  with a friendly feel.  The regulars are greeted by name entering and leaving.  While the brewed drinks are slow getting out,  they have an urn of pre- made coffee with instructions to leave your money in the tin. Essentially an Express lane. I prefer the brewed selections which are really superior to almost anywhere I've tried.<//text>

Born and raised in NYC and tbh their pizza is alright. I wouldn't call it NY style but somewhat close. (Not really). I order a large pie with the hope of getting a NY style pizza and tbh the cheese tasted a little funny like it was expired 2 days ago. <Rate>5< /Rate><date>1603679703144< /date><GmapID>0x80c2dbddf4c92843:0x30051541cd2b9e9b<//GmapID>< pics>

<UserId.>103894656940879353310<//UserId.>< review>
I was apprehensive of this spot, after looking at the prices and some of the other negative reviews. I decided to take a chance because I was really craving a good calzone (insert Parks & Rec meme). Having used to work at a family-owned NY/NJ style that made calzones, my standards were set pretty high.

When I got my order of knots and the calzone, I was blown away. The Calzone itself was baked to perfection, the toppings were plentiful and the cheese gooey. Not to mention the seasoning on top to finish it off was nothing short of BEAUTIFUL. The knots were a bit smaller than I'd hoped for being 4 dollars but what they lacked in size they made up for in taste and seasoning. Marinara sauce is nothing to write home about but it's much better than the chains. The (presumably) homemade ranch was a little thicker than I would have liked but nonetheless was great. All in all, I'll be ordering here again. You guys have blown me away as a first time customer, well done lads.< /review>

< review>
Edited Review:
Knocked them down to a three, thanks to the owner. Made a rude, snarky comment saying I owe him money because his employee under-charged me by $5 the week before. I'm leaving my original review below, because it is good pizza; but, the business lost my 2-3 orders per week because of the owner.

Amazing food accompanied with great service.  So far, I've eaten their buffalo wings, calzone, pizza, and salad.  Wings have a different spice and kick than other restaurants.  Calzone and pizza portions are large and valuable.  Salad is only thing I can't rave about, it's a regular traditional green salad topped with red onion, olives, and tomatoes. Definitely my favorite pizza in my area and a must try.</review>

<rate>3<//rate><Text>The training was ok but the issue i have was me receiving my guard card

its goin to be goin on almost two years and still have not received it

called bsis and they swear they sent it like two times then they said i would have to pay for another one when i never got the any guard card

I looked up my license number online and they had my name spelled wrong and my zip code was wrong as well still no guard card in my mail box i was so excited about becoming a security guard and still to this day i have no card smh i prefer you find a professional place to get your guard training and guard card.<//Text>< Pics>

<gmap_id>0x80c2b649631662b1:0x3b5ce120a414774c<//gmap_id><username>Nefertari A.<//username>< UserId.>
109042025486473706867<//UserId.>
< rate>
5< /rate>
<Time>1584497916312</Time><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8uyybQ2WUFyWaLvR_r7KmA4JzCgQjyo2kq7Hq=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><Response>None</Response>< Text>
Great spot to train with probably the best prices in town. Did my pepper spray and baton training here recently and it was easy. Received both certifications same day. Laminating machine was locked away so couldn't get them laminated there and the typewriter was locked in the main office and Craig (owner) was already gone for the day. Day after a holiday so I'm not gonna knock off any stars. Everything had to be written in. She (the receptionist/assistant) said I was welcome to come back to get everything typed and laminated next day but it's not a big deal. They are valid whether typed or not. I can get them laminated for a few cents each at Fed Ex or a dollar at Staples. Easy peasy.

Staff is also welcoming and friendly. Things can get a little slow at times, but not painfully slow. Mainly a lot going on and sometimes not enough staff to attend every need. Live Scan is what takes the longest because you have to wait for the people who do the live scanning to get there. Thankfully what I came for, didn't require any live scan or state fees. But at least I know what to expect when I come in for my FireArm processing whenever the time comes.

Pepper Spray and Baton cards do not expire as long as your guard card stays valid.

I'm happy because now I can start my new position next week! In less than a month, I will also be returning to do my firearm qualification since my job will require it. Again, cheapest prices I've seen with everything included. I think it's $371 for everything including the course, the range, gun rental, ammunition, live scan and state fees. Plus they train you for like 2 calibers; any additional calibers added on are like $20 each (I THINK; but check to make sure) which is great. Re-qual is $40 per caliber I believe.

Most other places are in the $500 to $700 range for everything included and only train you for maybe 3 different calibers. Classroom course is there onsite and is walk-in welcome on any day. Range day is every Wednesday. So no matter what day you start, jusy remember that range day is always the following Wednesday.

It is completely worth it to invest in your career as a security officer, ladies and gentlemen. Getting your guard card is half the battle, because at least you can get a nice steady job. But if you want to be able to make more money, upgrade and get more licenses. It's worth it. Even getting just your pepper spray and handcuff licenses can qualify you for better paying work. CPR/First Aid is also very inexpensive here, I believe it's $40 to get the card, and $30 to renew after that. Taser license only $100.

*Update I now have my firearm license as well. It took a little longer than it was supposed to but that is no fault of American Training Academy; it is the fault.of BSIS. My background check and everything went through, but somehow they overlooked my application and forgot to push it through and send the letter for the assessment. After a few phone calls to BSIS, I was finally able to get the ball rolling and I now have my firearm license in hand, laminated and all.

Thank you, American Training Academy! See you in June or July for re-qual and to possibly add on one more caliber! I hope you get lots of business I've been referring everyone over to you guys!<//Text>

< review>
This is a delightful spot with sweet, rustic decor and a homely feel. The staff are friendly and there's even a gorgeous cat that roams around. I got a latte and headed into the hot tub with my boyfriend where we had a relaxing hour. An hour is enough, we actually got out and had to rest because it was so warm. Very relaxing and well kept tub with a button for bubbles too. There's a light so you know how much time you have left so you're not worrying about when to get out. And it's pretty cheap. Definitely recommend for relaxation or a romantic date!</review>

< review>
I love Cafe Mokka but the fact that in 2019 they still can not accept cards is unacceptable.

Over all the drinks are great and the atmosphere is fantastic. I love the redwood trees that are in next to the tub.

If you go, go for an hour, it's worth it but be ready to go through the hassle of writing a check or bringing cash.

If they add cards as a payment method, even if they charge a $1 service fee or something I will update this review to 5‚≠ê</review>

< review>
A beautiful place to relax and read with a coffee or tea. It has a very natural feel, with solid wood table and benches. With a coy pond and plants in a walking garden out back in a fenced space with trees, it feels like you are no longer in town. It is a great place to catch an old fashioned Finnish tub or sauna as well, as you can rent a private tub or sauna for you and your friends by the half hour. It is like a retreat just five minutes away, from anywhere in town.<//review>

<Name>Sarah Jones< /Name><time>1555680661681<//time><Rating>5<//Rating><review>A tiny Finnish style coffee house with loose leaf teas and small delectable treats both sweet and savory. Hot tubs are about 6' in diameter with wooden benches for sitting and soaking, and a small wooden deck surrounding located in their own small, private outdoor area with ferns and tree cover. Careful, it can be slippery! There are steps up to climb in the tub, but you can request a low tub if climbing stairs is a challenge for you as it is for me. There is a button to press for jets which delivery an invigorating massage through three levels of jets : upper, mid, lower back. There is an outdoor shower for your convenience and usually a pump soap dispenser for all-in-one shampoo -shower gel washing pre and post soaking. A half-hour goes by so quickly, so watch for the green light to turn to yellow so you have time to shower off if you'd like, but please get out and into your dressing room when the light turns red so that the next patrons can enjoy their full time of soaking. You can bring your own towels, or get one there for Just .50cents more. You can also bring your own supplies to make it your own experience, but please don't add ANYTHING into the hot tub such as essential oils or soaps because the next patrons may have a severe allergy and although the filters are very good, the water is only changed two days a week to conserve water.   Just awesome! Enjoy!</review>< pics>
None</pics>

<Name>Jesse Robertson< /Name>< time>
1491670082582</time>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Cafe Mokka has been an Arcata favorite for decades. Behind the cafe, hot tub and sauna cabins surround a frog pond. The hot tubs are outdoors within privately fenced enclosures beneath the canopy of an "enchanted forest." The cafe resembles a cottage from Finland and has a cozy seating area with a fireplace. There is often live acoustic  music on the weekends in the evening. The coffee, hot chocolate, and mochas are always delicious. Both the coffee and the hot tubs are very reasonably priced.<//review>

<text>Dropped off my car nearly 4 weeks ago for what I thought would be a quick visit. I brought in my check engine light codes, told them to give it a once over to see what needed to be done and signed the paperwork with a "Promised delivery" of 5pm that same day... Still don't have it back.

Timeline:
Monday January 25th, I drop off the car at my 8:30am appointment time, explain all I mentioned above, and they send me home in a lyft and tell me they'll call when they know more.

Since I hadn't heard anything after a few hours I called to get a status update around noon. They hadn't even started on my vehicle yet, and finally decided to tell me that the codes i brought in meant they needed to do a complete tear down of the engine.

I checked in daily to see if there were any updates, i was told on Friday the 29th that they thought it was my timing chain and they still needed to do a tear down.

Saturday the 30th, I was able to get a loaner through them, after needing to get a rental earlier in the week because they hadn't started on my car yet.

I followed up on Monday and was told that they had no information for me yet.

Tuesday, February 2nd I'm finally told that the tear down has begun. I check in a few times that week but don't get any information until the next Tuesday February 9th.

Feb 9th, i get a list of repairs and parts that will cost more than what the car is worth, at this point I'm already considering just abandoning it and buying a vehicle at another dealer just to get things over with.

A week and a half later brings us to today, February 18th where I'm still driving the loaner they got for me, which has been the only upside so far in their service, and still waiting to see how much more than the worth of my car I'm going to be charged when I'm frankly considering leaving it to be their problem if I don't get more information or even better, my car which right now feels like I'll be lucky to see before the end of the month, even though I've already been given two possible ETAs.

I understand that parts take time to ship and repairs can take a while, but the lack of communication up front has locked me into being in their shop's mercy for the last three and a half weeks, which if I had been told up front that I might be a month before I saw my car again, I would have gone somewhere else right from the start.

I've been told they might be able to swing some discounts or cut off some hours of labor, but at this point I don't know if I'll trust the totals I'm shown because it's been in their shop for so long and I have no way to contest or question whatever they decide to tell me they've done.

Now, if I get my car back and all is well I may come bump this rating up, but so far the two stars is only because my main point of contact has been patient with my nearly daily requests for information and the fact that I was given a loaner to use in the meantime.

I haven't decided yet, but I may never be using this shop or dealership again in the future. I try to give the benefit of the doubt and as much patience as I can manage, but this has honestly been ridiculous.

-A frustrated customer who just wants his car back and to not have to be homeless to pay for it.< /text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None</Resp><gmap_id>0x80c2d90c044c0461:0x3c48a649be676d73< /gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

I was very impressed that Rudy and his team were not pushing me into getting the car.  In-fact, Rudy told me that if I was able to wait one day, he would be able to get me a better deal since he could speak to another department the next day.  Even though he could have "closed the deal" on the spot, he did what was best for me as the customer, and took additional steps to get me a more favorable deal.  Very impressed!

Rudy came through with his promise, and called me early the next day to tell me everything was approved.  He then set an appointment for me to come-by that day to meet with his partner, Corey, so that I could be in and out as soon as possible.

I sat down with Steve in the finance department, and he explained all of the finance details, and gave me lots of helpful additional information on my new electric car.  Steve continued the trend of not being pushy, and taking his time to ensure I understood everything I was signing.

The most impressive part came at the end of the purchase.  My wife needed to sign a form for our trade-in, but she was unable to make it down to the dealership for a few days.  Corey and Rudy arranged for Gus to drive to my house (more than 15 miles away) in rush hour, so that my wife could sign the form there.  Gus showed-up on-time, explained everything to my wife about what she was signing, asked us if we had any other questions, and was friendly throughout the entire process.  UNBELIEVABLE CUSTOMER SERVICE!

Anyways, super impressed across the board.  Thanks for helping me out.

Keep up the good work!</Text>

On the day of purchase, Doug was off work, and Gustavo J. bravely stepped in and handled the not-so-fun negotiation over several hours; and came through for me to get the price I wanted.  He also drove for over two hours to bring the contract and car down to me over 100 miles away!  In addition, he stayed and answered all my questions, showed me features of the car, and did a little test drive with me, before going back home.  He really went out of his way to work with me!

Keep in mind that I had never stepped foot inside the dealership, and everything was done via email, phone and text.

I have been very pleased at the individual and team effort at Sierra Chevrolet. Thank you!<//Review>

< text>
1.0 star rating

7/10/2016

This dealer has something akin to a superiority complex. I recently brought my car in to have the airbag system diagnosed. I had just been rear ended and the car's airbag light had come on with the message "Service Airbag." After talking to some mechanics and doing some of my own research online, I came to the conclusion that, at a minimum, the system had to be reset. It could have sustained more damage as well, as the seat belts had locked up, but for sure I was not going to escape the $100+ it would cost to reset the system. OK. I accepted that. So I brought it in and the parts representative confirmed that resetting the system would cost me at least $100+. My dad and I dropped off the car and the next day we came back inquiring on the vehicle. We were given a statement of work in excess of $4000 with the explanation that everything comprising the airbag system, with the exception of the airbag itself, since it did not deploy, would have to be replaced. This included the computer modules, the sensors, the seat belts, and all this other stuff. I then told the manager at the dealer that when the appraiser for the at fault party appraised the damage, he could only appraise what he could see from the outside. Since all of this was internal, this was not part of his appraisal. The appraiser's explicit instructions were to have whomever inspected the vehicle (that being the dealer here) contact the appraiser directly to discuss additional issues. The manager was absolutely adamant on NOT talking to the appraiser. "We do not deal with insurance," he said. "That is YOUR responsibility. YOU work it out with them." So let me get this straight. Most likely, the dealer is overcharging me with this statement of work because prior to showing up at the dealer, I had gotten some estimates that were significantly lower from some body shops regarding the airbag system. Yet I am giving the dealer a chance to make some money, but oh, he cannot be bothered with spending any of his precious time or energy dealing with the nitty gritty of contacting the insurance company who will actually be paying for this on my behalf. Could this be because he very well knows that he is overcharging significantly and that insurance will not agree to these exorbitant charges and so he figures that the best thing to do would be to go directly to me because I am an easy target for gouging? And then, of course, not only does he have to gouge me, he has to insult my dignity and my intelligence by instructing and educating me in a rather patronizing way that it is not the dealer's responsibility to deal with insurance bureaucracy but rather, the onus falls on the victim, who has already been traumatized enough with being in an accident. So I think I am beginning to construct in my mind what the mantra of this dealer is regarding its customers. 1. BS the customer, 2. Gouge the customer, 3. Insult the customer, and 4. Drive away the customer. OK. Point made. Since the dealer does not want my business, the dealer won't get it. Now or ever.<//text>

< review>
I called in and set up an appointment with Joanne. She was super nice, and set me up with an appt. I came in today and walked into the service office. Three men were there, and two looked busy. I approach the third and he just stares at me. He's sitting in the chair... no actually the chair and he have become one. It was as if the chair absorbed his soul and was working him like a puppet. I had already locked eyes and begun the approach so I proceeded.

At this point "Rolando, the chair puppet" gives me a "whatdoyouwantwhydoyoucomeinhereandbotherme?" kind of a greeting. I said that I wanted to get my car repaired, and that the oxygen sensor is acting up. I said I have a warranty contract that I purchased at the Henry Curtis Ford in Petaluma when I bought the car used. I said while you have my car could you see if there is anything else that needs repairing while you're at it. He said "We don't do that. We will only tell you about something if we see it broken in the midst of fixing the problem. You know, like if a part is hanging or something." I look up at their services and fees board, point to the 'Vehicle Inspection N/C' line item. "What's that?" I ask. He says all chipper "That's our 28 point inspection (starts to trail off because he knows he's been caught)... uh we uh check the tire pressure and stuff"

I'm really feeling like his approach to his job is a "Prove your worth and then maybe I'll help you" style. Last I checked we were in a capitalistic society... you know, a 'I give you money and you help me' economy. I guess I stepped into the Club 54 repair place.

Then Rolando comments on my warranty, "I've never seen that warranty before".

"I bought it at the Henry Curtis Ford up in Petaluma"

"Never heard of it. We're GMC." turns to another guy (Jeff) "You heard of this?" Jeff saif no. "All I'm saying is if they pay by check we won't take it"

Now I'm a tad bit aggitated, and when I say a tad bit I mean like the Cuban government and the US government are a tad bit different. I say to Rolando "Aren't you supposed to try the sweets before the punishment?"

He takes my contract and leans over to Jeff with it. "You wanna help this guy? Evidently I'm not nice enough for him."

Wow. Gotta say that I was impressed by the carefree abandon in which he approaches his job security. Rolando, oh giver of annoyance, harbinger of nay saying. I hope one day the chair will release you and you can enjoy life once again...

I'm posting this even though they still have my car. I hope he doesn't spit on the engine or snip my brake lines.</review>

<Text>Great counter type breakfast and lunch spot!< /Text><userid>113175149001429112969<//userid><GmapID>0x808f7fcc625419af:0x9a8fb86da516cef4< /GmapID><rating>5</rating></record></dataset><record>
< rating>
4<//rating>
<Pictures>None</Pictures><GmapID>0x808f7fcc625419af:0x9a8fb86da516cef4</GmapID><Name>Ergin Guney</Name><response>None</response>< user_id>
107117291446401236439</user_id>
< time>
1511389826406</time>
< Text>
Open only on weekdays, this is a reassuringly old-fashioned lunch joint. The portion sizes are large and the prices are reasonable. You wouldn't expect the quality of the food at a place like this to win awards, and it doesn't, but I've never had anything here to complain about. You can expect a few hot entrees that change daily, along with a fairly extensive permanent menu. The selection outside the hot entrees consist mainly of sandwiches, burgers, and salads, though you can also quickly grab a prepackaged bagel with cream cheese. Actually, the quality of their salads may surprise you, and they carry both prepackaged salads as well as at least a ceasar salad that you can order at the counter. You can polish your meal with a pick from among several options of pastries and donuts. Their fridge is stuffed with an impressively wide selection of bottled drinks and their salty snack and candy bar selection is also wider than what I'd consider average for a place of this scale. There are 10 or so small tables inside and two or three two-person tables just outside the door, but no one would call this place spacious. The flow that consists of ordering at the counter, picking up your food, and paying at the cashier is not exactly streamlined, so this ordering-and-paying process could get a little clogged and confusing when things are really busy at the height of the lunch rush. When the place is more empty, you won't even notice any problem with this though.</Text>

< Review>
Hot wings and televisions.  That pretty much sums up Buffalo Wild Wings.  The wings are actually pretty good and they have a wide range of sauces from mild to burning.  The TV's are all over, but mounted high enough that you can avoid seeing them all the time, and they leave the sound off.  Which is good, because that much sports TV is way too much to talk over.  The service at lunch was fast and the wait staff was good.<//Review>

<Review>First time getting wings from this restaurant.  The online ordering experience was quick and easy.  The price was reasonable.  Picking up the order was also quick with a friendly staff.  The wings, traditional wings with Buffalo medium hot sauce, did not meet my expectation.  I ate tons of wings when I went to school in Buffalo, NY and this was not it..

Update 7/24.  Take-out service was friendly and quick.  After I get home I found that the celery and carrots were missing.  I ordered with sauce on the side and I liked it better this way.  3 stars.

Update 8/20.  Take-out service was friendly and quick again.  The celery and carrots were in the bag.  I ordered with the sauce on the side.  The wings were really dry this time.  Back to 2 stars.

If you wondered why I kept going back since I thought the wings were mediocre.  Well, cause I have a $100 gift card that I want to use up.  Maybe I should order something other than the wings next time?</Review></record>

< Text>
I'm a big fan of boneless chicken "wings".  Buffalo Wild Wings is usually my favorite simply because they have some a great selection of sauces to go with it.  Also, their lunch prices can't really be beat (maybe $10 for 8 wings, celery & carrots and a side).  The service is "ok", though they never really seem particularly upbeat/happy to be there.

My one big negative for BWW is that they seem to skimp on the amount of sauce on the wings!</Text>

<GmapID>0x808fc76b4882a269:0x779a511bbae4cca2< /GmapID><review>I only go on Tuesdays, so this review is only for Tuesday nights... for the inexpensive wings. They are great. The onion rings are also the best I've had anywhere. But this is also when everyone else wants cheap wings, and this location has not figured out how to deal with the demand, especially when a game is on (it gets very loud too). Not sure who is to blame, but the wait time to be seated is about 30 minutes on average after 7pm, and after you order your food it takes another 30 minues to an hour for it to come out of the kitchen. Granted, they do warn you about the wait ahead of time. Ive started to order the wings to-go, and giving myself an hour before I leave to pick them up. It seems like many people have started doing this as well since the wait times for to-go orders have been increasing. Maybe some day they'll figure out a way to work the crowds. It's my favorite wing place! But make sure you have some time to spend.< /review><rate>4< /rate>< Response>

There was not many people at the restaurant but still our server was not around very often. When we asked the server for an extra plate to put some food on for a child we received a speech about how they do not give out extra plates or bowls but if we wanted a piece of wax paper they could do that. I was pretty shocked at this but ok no need to argue about this new learned rule. Wings, chicken tenders, burgers and salads is what they do and the food all tasted and looked like it was dumped out of a foster farms bag in the freezer and nuked for a couple minutes. To end our fantastic day at their establishment our server who we could not find at times took the time to calculate and hand write the percentages and tip amounts based on our bill on the check. I am assuming their registers do not have this capability and also she was just trying to help us from working the math out ourselves. Bravo buffalo wild wings for making sure I never return again.< /review>

<text>Surprisingly, my most recent experience at BWW greatly surpassed my expectations in terms of service. Our waitress was friendly and to be honest, I thought she was pretty cool. 4 minutes before happy hour ended, we reached out for her attention and told her we were trying to squeeze in our drink orders before happy hour ended, she understood fully and made it her mission. She came back with a grin on her face and told us we're set and then proceeded to take our orders. Not too long later, the food came out and she left us to it, checking up on us once or twice. "Do you guys need anything....*scans the table for a second* you need napkins!"

Her service alone deserves 5 stars, but if I'm being completely honest, the past couple times I've been here had subpar and spotty service. Not to mention, I'm really reviewing the food here right?

FOOD:
Boneless -- Extremely dry, tough pieces of chicken.. They weren't even warm. Nearly $10 for a snack size??? I could have bought a large bag from the grocery store and microwaved it for that price and it would still taste better.. Disappointing.

Traditional Wings -- It seemed like my friends really enjoyed their half off deal. $10 for a large size (20 pieces) of wings was not a bad deal.

Basket of fries -- the highlight of my meal personally... Seasoned with buffalo dry-rub and freshly fried, these were good. Unfortunately the spices built up in my mouth quickly and I was too *chicken* (hehe..) to continue my quest in finishing it. On the bright side, I REALLY enjoyed my Racer 5 IPA because of it.

BWW is a good place to catch up with friends over some drinks, but pick and choose your time wisely or you'll end up waiting a long time for a spot when you can just go elsewhere. Experience is entirely based on who you get as your waiter/waitress. Food is nothing special.< /text></record></dataset><record>
